World War I animated a set of top-down economic policies that elevated owners, smothered workers, and imposed a rigid economic hierarchy across their societies. Where these policies “succeeded,” relatively speaking, was in their enrichment of certain parties, including employers and foreign-trade interests, who accumulated power and capital at the expense of labor. Here, Mattei argues, is where the true value of austerity can be observed: its insulation of entrenched privilege and its elimination of all alternatives to capitalism. Drawing on newly uncovered archival material from Britain and Italy, much of it translated for the first time, The Capital Order offers a damning and essential new account of the rise of austerity—and of modern economics—at the levers of contemporary political power.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aCapitalismzGreat Britain. 0aCapitalismzItaly. 0aFascismzGreat Britain. 0aFascismzItaly. 0aStagnation (Economics). 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh  aeconomics, capitalism, capital, solvency, public benefits, fiscal spending, wages, austerity, economic policy, financial crisis, government, social welfare, nonfiction, history, politics, workers, labor, business, world war i, power, working-class, italy, interwar britain, privilege, foreign-trade, employers, fascism, control, class, wealth, oppression, inflation, resistance.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076650940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226818405423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226818405/original  a978-3-11-076650-9  University of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles